{{Cite sources|date=October 2019}}
'''Suwa Region''' (諏訪地域) refers to an area in the southern part of {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s Minami-Shin region, centered around the cities of {{ill|Okaya|ja|岡谷市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Suwa|ja|諏訪市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Chino|ja|茅野市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is one of the ten administrative regions designated by the prefecture.<ref>[https://www.pref.nagano.lg.jp/koho/10koiki/suwa.html Information on the Suwa Region], Nagano Prefecture website (accessed August 3, 2018).</ref> This area corresponds closely to the former {{ill|Suwa District|ja|諏訪郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
As of 2019, the region's population was 194,439. Except for Hara Village, most municipalities in the area are experiencing a population decline, with particularly severe decreases in {{ill|Shimosuwa|ja|下諏訪町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Okaya City, and Suwa City. The region is characterized by a multi-core structure centered on its three main cities, with Chino City being the most populous.
The {{ill|Chūō Main Line|ja|中央本線|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Chūō Expressway|ja|中央自動車道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} pass through the area, serving as key transport routes connecting {{ill|Kantō Region|ja|関東地方|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yamanashi Prefecture|ja|山梨県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and the {{ill|Tōkai Region|ja|東海地方|qq=draft|qq=draft}} while avoiding the Southern Alps.
== Overview == === Municipalities === The Suwa Region encompasses the following municipalities, stretching from west to east: * {{ill|Okaya|ja|岡谷市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Suwa|ja|諏訪市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Chino|ja|茅野市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * Suwa District: ** {{ill|Shimosuwa|ja|下諏訪町|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ** {{ill|Fujimi|ja|富士見町|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ** {{ill|Hara|ja|原村|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
The region can be broadly divided into two areas: - The "Lake Area" (west side) encompassing the three municipalities surrounding {{ill|Lake Suwa|ja|諏訪湖|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. - The "Yatsugatake Foothills" (east side), including Chino City, Hara Village, and Fujimi Town.
=== Geography === The Suwa Region is located approximately 200 km from Tokyo and Nagoya, connected by the Chūō Expressway and the JR Chūō Main Line. * '''Mountains''': {{ill|Mount Tateshina|ja|蓼科山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yatsugatake|ja|八ヶ岳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Mount Kirigamine|ja|霧ヶ峰|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * '''Rivers''': Miyagawa River, Kamikawa River, Nakamongawa River * '''Lakes''': Lake Suwa, {{ill|Lake Shirakaba|ja|白樺湖|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Lake Tateshina|ja|蓼科湖|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
=== Climate === The region's climate varies significantly due to its topography. Areas near Lake Suwa tend to experience warmer summers and drier winters due to the Foehn effect, while the Yatsugatake Foothills are cooler in summer and have harsher winters, with climates akin to those of Hokkaido.
=== Economy === The Suwa Region has a history of silk production, later transitioning to a precision machinery industry. The {{ill|Suwa Area Industrial Messe|ja|諏訪圏工業メッセ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, an industrial trade fair, highlights the area's manufacturing capabilities.
== History == === Ancient === The region's human activity dates back to the Jomon and Yayoi periods, with artifacts such as obsidian tools found at sites like Wada Pass.
=== Medieval to Early Modern Period === During the Sengoku period, the Suwa clan governed the region, with prominent figures like {{ill|Suwa Yorishige|ja|諏訪頼重|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. After various conflicts, the clan was re-established under Suwa Yorimoto and later served the Tokugawa shogunate as lords of the Takashima Domain.
=== Modern === - 1871: Abolition of the domain system; incorporated into Takashima Prefecture and later Nagano Prefecture. - 1981: Chūō Expressway opens, improving regional connectivity.
== Tourism == The Suwa Region is a prominent tourist destination, drawing millions annually with attractions such as: - {{ill|Suwa Grand Shrine|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a nationally renowned Shinto shrine complex. - {{ill|Takashima Castle|ja|高島城|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, known as one of Japan’s three famous lakeside castles. - Numerous hot springs, including {{ill|Kamisuwa Onsen|ja|上諏訪温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Shimosuwa Onsen|ja|下諏訪温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
=== Museums and Galleries === - {{ill|Kitazawa Museum of Art|ja|北澤美術館|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - {{ill|Chino City Tateshina Archaeological Museum|ja|茅野市尖石縄文考古館|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
=== Natural Attractions === - {{ill|Lake Suwa|ja|諏訪湖|qq=draft|qq=draft}} - {{ill|Mount Kirigamine|ja|霧ヶ峰|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
== Transportation == * '''Rail''': JR Chūō Main Line, with major stations such as Kamisuwa and Chino. * '''Road''': Chūō Expressway and Route 20, serving as primary thoroughfares.
== References == {{Reflist}} == See Also == * {{ill|Suwa Area Federation|ja|諏訪広域連合|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
== External Links == * [https://www.pref.nagano.lg.jp/koho/10koiki/suwa.html Official Suwa Region Information]
